Ad Sicyonem oppogrtandum] Cf. Ep. 19. 9, and 20. 4. It is a playful allusion to certain payments which were due to Atticus from Sicyon, either in his capacity of publicanus, or else on account of a loan which he had· advanced to the state. The former is the more probable theory, for we find that about this time Sicyon, as one of the liberi populi, received certain exemptione from tribute which were an evi· dent loss to the com any who farmed her taxes.
